{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639076"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17761"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17761"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.18,0,0.23,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10475"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"1963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of progressive sensory changes. She was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis three months ago. Despite treatment, her symptoms have worsened. She reports a loss of proprioception and vibration sense in all areas of the body below the C8 level. However, she does not experience any loss of pain or temperature sensation, and her motor function remains intact. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely occurring?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior cord syndrome","Anterior cord syndrome","Central cord syndrome","Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome","Cauda equina syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by the loss of proprioception and vibration sense while preserving pain, temperature, and motor function. This pattern of sensory loss is due to damage to the dorsal columns of the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E results in loss of motor function and pain and temperature sensation, with preservation of proprioception and vibration sense.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E usually affects the upper limbs more than the lower limbs and involves motor impairment, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrown-S\u00e9quard syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves hemisection of the spinal cord, leading to ipsilateral loss of proprioception and motor function and contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauda equina syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves lower motor neuron signs, such as flaccid paralysis and loss of reflexes, along with sensory loss in a saddle distribution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple sclerosis can cause demyelination in the spinal cord, leading to posterior cord syndrome.","Posterior cord syndrome is characterised by loss of proprioception and vibration sense, with preservation of pain, temperature, and motor function.","The absence of pain, temperature, and motor loss helps differentiate posterior cord syndrome from other spinal cord syndromes."],"references":["McKinley W, Santos K, Meade M, Brooke K. Incidence and outcomes of spinal cord injury clinical syndromes. J Spinal Cord Med. 2007;30(3):215-24. doi: 10.1080/10790268.2007.11753929. PMID: 17684887; PMCID: PMC2031952.","McKinley W, Hills A, Sima A. Posterior cord syndrome: Demographics and rehabilitation outcomes. J Spinal Cord Med. 2021 Mar;44(2):241-246. doi: 10.1080/10790268.2019.1585135. Epub 2019 Apr 2. PMID: 30939076; PMCID: PMC7952058.","Kennamer BT, DelPino BJ, Lettieri SC, Gridley DG, Hollingworth AK, Feiz-Erfan I. Blunt traumatic posterior cord syndrome. Spinal Cord Ser Cases. 2022 May 11;8(1):52. doi: 10.1038/s41394-022-00485-y. PMID: 35545621; PMCID: PMC9095631.","McKinley W, Hills A, Sima A. Posterior cord syndrome: Demographics and rehabilitation outcomes. J Spinal Cord Med. 2021 Mar;44(2):241-246. doi: 10.1080/10790268.2019.1585135. Epub 2019 Apr 2. PMID: 30939076; PMCID: PMC7952058."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17761"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T11:07:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T11:08:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10475"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77522"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{